    <div class="rightSection" id="process">
        <h2>QC Process</h2>
        <p1>
            It is QC's responsibility to perform a practical test to ensure that the consumer's reported symptom (CRS) has been resolved. There are a few other routine tests and checks that we perform as well, but this is the primary function of QC. The following
            steps may be performed in no particular order, and the efficiency of the sequence may vary based on symptom. Nevertheless, <b>all</b> of the following steps must be performed before completing QC. Be sure to mark each step as you
            go through the process.
            <h3>Symptom Resolution Verification</h3>
            For all repairs, you must read the work order, and all consumer letters and notes to understand the symptom they asked us to resolve. The testing you must perform to verify the symptom is resolved will vary based upon the reported symptom, but here are
            some example scenarios:
            <br>Read the following procedures to understand how this may be accomplished:
            <li style="list-style-type: none;"><a href="https://nintendo.sharepoint.com/sites/techsvc/NX/Pages/Referenced_Procedures_JC.aspx#verify" target="_blank">Symptom Resolution Verification</a></li>
            <li style="list-style-type: none;"><a href="https://nintendo.sharepoint.com/sites/techsvc/NX/Pages/Referenced_Procedures_JC.aspx#sticks" target="_blank">Analog Check/Calibration</a> - Nintendo pays particularly close attention to ensure that each of the 8 directions of the
                joycon analog are checked <b>at least 3 times before you may conclude that the symptom is not occurring.</b></li>
            <li style="list-style-type: none;"><a href="https://nintendo.sharepoint.com/sites/techsvc/NX/Pages/Referenced_Procedures_JC.aspx#buttons" target="_blank">Test Buttons</a>Check each button once before passing the JoyCon.</li>
            <h3>Visual Inspection</h3>
            <li style="list-style-type: none;"><a href="https://nintendo.sharepoint.com/sites/techsvc/NX/Pages/Referenced_Procedures_JC.aspx#visual" target="_blank">Follow these instructions to perform the Visual Inspection.
                <br> <b>Please take care to insure that the rail buttons match the color of the JoyCon Housing. It is possible that the incorrect color could be installed at repair.</b></a></li>
            Check to ensure there are no cracks in the housing, particularly near the "Lock Release" button, as this is a common area for cracks and damage.
            <br><img src="./img/jctriage/crackedhousing.jpg" alt="crackedhousing">
            <br>Also, <b>always</b> ensure that the joycon lock adequately prevents the JoyCon from coming loose from the HAC console without holding the lock release.
            <br><img src="./img/jctriage/lockweargood.jpg" alt="lockweargood"><img src="./img/jctriage/lockwearng.jpg" alt="lockwearng">
            <h3>Sync and Charge</h3>
            <li style="list-style-type: none;"><a href="https://nintendo.sharepoint.com/sites/techsvc/NX/Pages/Referenced_Procedures_JC.aspx#wired" target="_blank">Follow these instructions to perform the Sync and Charge verification.</a></li>
