    <div class="rightSection" id="cleaning">
        <h2>Cleaning the JoyCon</h2>
        <p1>
            Prior to passing QC, we are required to gently clean/wipe the HAC console with a mixture of alcohol and water AND ammonia-free Windex.
            <ul>
                <li>First, clean the surface of the JoyCon with the alcohol/water mixture using a microfiber towel.
                    <div style="color:red"><b>Do not use excessive alcohol, as this can cause damage to the unit. A single dab on the towel is likely sufficient.</b></div>
                    <img src="./img/jcqc/alcoholdispenser.jpg" alt="Alcohol" style="height:40vh">
                </li>
                <li>Wait for the unit to dry, which should only take a few moments since alcohol quickly evaporates. Alternatively, you can use a <u><b>separate</b></u> dry microfiber towel. </li>
                <li><span style="color:red"><b>Using a separate microfiber towel,</span> wipe the surface of the JoyCon with Ammonia-Free Windex only. Blue windex is not Ammonia-Free, and is not acceptable per Nintendo of America.</b>
                    <br><img src="./img/jcqc/windexaf.jpg" alt="Windex" style="height:40vh"> </li>
                <li>Again, wait for the unit to dry, which should only take a few moments since windex quickly evaporates. Alternatively, you can use a <u><b>separate</b></u> dry microfiber towel. </li>
                <li>Insert the JoyCon into a plastic bag, and tape it shut. Ensure the unit is dry before doing this.
                    <br><img src="img/jcqc/baggedJC.jpg" alt="BaggedJC" style="height:30vh">
                </li>
            </ul>
            <br> If there are more than 2 ROs in a box, affix a numbered sticker to the RO label on the box and its corresponding joycon. The number signifies to the next operator which joycon corresponds to an RO, since we'll be pulling the paperwork
            out after writeup.
            <br><img src="./original (old)/writeupworkinstructions_files/sticker.jpg" alt="RO Validation" style="width:auto;height:400px">
        </p1>
    </div>
    <div class="rightSection" id="failureHandling">
        <p1>
            <h2>Failure Handling</h2>
            Failures in QC will likely result in the JoyCon being swapped. When a true failure occurs, label the joycon with the RO number by writing on a piece of masking tape using a marker. Do not use a pen, as this will scratch the JoyCon. Mark the traveler to
            denote that you are exchanging the JoyCon, and cross out the repair/testing sections to ensure that the intention to exchange the JoyCon is clear. Test all other joycons in the box and handle them accordingly before placing the box in the
            designated location to go to swap.
            <br><img src="img/jcrepair/jccore.png" alt="JC Core" style="height:auto"><img src="img/jcrepair/swapfromtest.jpg" alt="Swap" style="height:40vh"></li>

        </p1>
